@zajanksk  - chaincode is executed during the endorsement phase.  Each endorsing peer runs the chaincode and if there is no error responds with a signed endorsement response.  The endorsement response contains the actual state changes (they have not yet been committed) and the signature is over the entire response.

After the transaction along with collected endorsements is sent to the orderer and then sent to the peers, each peer than validates the transaction.  Part of the validation is to make sure that the transaction meets the endorsement policy.  As part of this check, the peer makes sure that enough signatures were collected over the SAME response.

So let's say the endorsement policy required 2 out of Org1,Org2,Org3.  If peers from Org1,Org2 and Org3 all returned different results, then the transaction would not be committed.  If the Org1 and Org2 return the same results, then the transaction would be committed

